5.1 Overall Considerations
The next figures show a comparison between:

Commanded position provided by the Raspberry Pi path planning;
FMU (Functional Mockup Unit) instance exported from Matlab Simulink machine’s model;
Real telemetry data from machine. In case of movement axes (X an Y), the logged data come from linear encoders, while for positioning axes (Z, A, C) the plotted quantity comes from the rotary encoders

It is possible to see how the 3 curves overlap between each other on all plots. An important consideration must be stated: A little delay is shown between the command and the real curves. It is caused by multiple factors: first, it arises from the PID’s following nature (the PID control requires an error to command an output), second, the commanded position’s timecode corresponds to the time instant at which it is output from the Raspberry. The machine feedback, instead, occurs after an SPI full duplex communication. So, when the setpoint is imposed to \(x_k\), the same SPI communication returns the machine’s feedback of the state \(x_{k-1}\).
